# 4. Java Module System (JPMS) – Required

This backend must use the **Java Platform Module System (JPMS)** to enforce domain boundaries at compile time.

Why JPMS belongs here:

* It is part of **code architecture**, not infrastructure
* It enforces DDD boundaries and prevents accidental cross-domain coupling
* It improves long-term maintainability and supports easier microservice extraction later

## 4.1 JPMS Module Mapping

Each domain is a separate **Java module**.

Example module names:

* `hestia.host`
* `hestia.invitation`
* `hestia.rsvp`
* `hestia.notification`
* `hestia.auth`
* `hestia.payment` (future)

## 4.2 Module Export Rules (Strict)

* Only a domain’s **API package** is exported.
* Domain internals are not exported.
* Infrastructure packages are not exported.

Example `module-info.java`:

```java
module hestia.invitation {
  requires spring.context;
  requires spring.beans;

  // If cross-domain access is required, depend on exported APIs only
  requires hestia.host;

  // Export only API contracts (DTOs, ports, public facades)
  exports com.hestia.invitation.api;
}
```

Notes:

* Cross-domain calls must go through exported APIs (ports/facades), not internal classes.
* No reflective access to bypass boundaries.

